<subSubSection id="93FABF9FF25FFFC4FC4EFA922BDDF105" pageId="2" pageNumber="642" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph id="DB5FEC14F25FFFC4FC4EFA922B2EF3C5" blockId="2.[899,1365,1405,1429]" box="[899,1365,1405,1429]" pageId="2" pageNumber="642">
<heading id="80175B78F25FFFC4FC4EFA922B2EF3C5" bold="true" box="[899,1365,1405,1429]" centered="true" fontSize="10" level="2" pageId="2" pageNumber="642" reason="2">
<emphasis id="E9943006F25FFFC4FC4EFA922B2EF3C5" bold="true" box="[899,1365,1405,1429]" pageId="2" pageNumber="642">
<taxonomicName id="1CE09797F25FFFC4FC4EFA922AEDF3C5" authorityName="Grootaert &amp; Puniamoorthy" authorityYear="2014" box="[899,1174,1405,1429]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Ngirhaphium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="642" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caeruleum">
<emphasis id="E9943006F25FFFC4FC4EFA922AEDF3C5" bold="true" box="[899,1174,1405,1429]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="642">Ngirhaphium caeruleum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species complex
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DB5FEC14F25FFFC4FCE0FA522BDDF105" blockId="2.[812,1453,1469,1877]" pageId="2" pageNumber="642">
The original described population of 
<taxonomicName id="1CE09797F25FFFC4FB7EFA512B39F385" authorityName="Grootaert &amp; Puniamoorthy" authorityYear="2014" box="[1203,1346,1469,1493]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Ngirhaphium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="642" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caeruleum">
<emphasis id="E9943006F25FFFC4FB7EFA512B39F385" box="[1203,1346,1469,1493]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="642">N. caeruleum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
consisted of large flies with a blue shine on the thorax and the abdomen and they were accordingly named 
<taxonomicName id="1CE09797F25FFFC4FB6CFA122B6AF045" authorityName="Grootaert &amp; Puniamoorthy" authorityYear="2014" box="[1185,1297,1533,1557]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Ngirhaphium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="642" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caeruleum">
<emphasis id="E9943006F25FFFC4FB6CFA122B6AF045" box="[1185,1297,1533,1557]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="642">caeruleum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which means blue in Latin. Actually a large population was found on the island of Semakau (
<figureCitation id="43DBF091F25FFFC4FBF0F9D22AFAF005" box="[1085,1153,1597,1621]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[113,148,979,1001]" captionTargetBox="[92,1469,170,978]" captionTargetId="figure-421@2.[92,1469,170,978]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 1. Haplotype network of the Ngirhaphium caeruleum-complex. Brunei: Berambang, Tutong, Labu; Singapore: Pulau Ubin, Pulau Tekong, Semakau Island; Thailand: Chumphon, Surat Thani, and Cambodia." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5343731" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5343731/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="642">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). However green metallic shining specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="1CE09797F25FFFC4FBD4F9B12AD0F025" authorityName="Grootaert &amp; Puniamoorthy" authorityYear="2014" box="[1049,1195,1629,1653]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Ngirhaphium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="642" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caeruleum">
<emphasis id="E9943006F25FFFC4FBD4F9B12AD0F025" box="[1049,1195,1629,1653]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="642">N. caeruleum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were found in southern 
<collectingCountry id="A3F7AC84F25FFFC4FCE3F9922DE8F0C5" box="[814,915,1661,1685]" name="Thailand" pageId="2" pageNumber="642">Thailand</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="A3F7AC84F25FFFC4FC6FF9922D8BF0C5" box="[930,1008,1661,1685]" name="Brunei" pageId="2" pageNumber="642">Brunei</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="A3F7AC84F25FFFC4FC32F9922A0BF0C5" box="[1023,1136,1661,1685]" name="Cambodia" pageId="2" pageNumber="642">Cambodia</collectingCountry>
and on some small islands around 
<collectingCountry id="A3F7AC84F25FFFC4FCB0F9722D96F0E5" box="[893,1005,1693,1717]" name="Singapore" pageId="2" pageNumber="642">Singapore</collectingCountry>
. Apart from their green body colour, their morphology and the male terminalia resemble the original population from Semakau Island in 
<collectingCountry id="A3F7AC84F25FFFC4FB7DF9322B64F0A5" box="[1200,1311,1757,1781]" name="Singapore" pageId="2" pageNumber="642">Singapore</collectingCountry>
, but differ in details. Here we paid attention to the shape and the bristling of the surstyli that are clasping organs. We compared it with the haplotypes based on the NGS barcodes (313 bp).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="93FABF9FF25FFFC2FCE0F8922F6FF165" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="644" pageId="2" pageNumber="642" type="description">
<paragraph id="DB5FEC14F25FFFC4FCE0F8922B7BFE45" blockId="2.[811,1453,1917,2069]" pageId="2" pageNumber="642">
<figureCitation id="43DBF091F25FFFC4FCE0F8922D06F1C5" box="[813,893,1917,1941]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[136,171,1820,1842]" captionTargetBox="[138,1474,294,1804]" captionTargetId="figure-8@3.[116,1482,277,1809]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 2. Ngirhaphium caeruleum-complex. View of inside of the dorsal surstylus of the left side and the fused dorsal and ventral surstyli of the right side. Scale = 0.1mm. A, green caeruleum from Tutong, Brunei (ZRCBDP0066395) at 1.6 % from the Semakau population; B, green caeruleum from Pulau Tekong, Singapore (ZRCBDP0001462) at 0.6% from the Semakau population; C, green caeruleum from Pulau Ubin, Singapore (ZRC_BDP_0084430) at 0.6% from the Semakau population; D, blue caeruleum from the type locality on Semakau Island, Singapore (ZRCBDP0118762); E, green thaicum, new species from Surat Thani, Thailand (24-018) at 4.2% from the Semakau population; F, green thaicum, new species from Cambodia (JP3C_Ngi-cambodiensis_Misc002) within the variability of the southern Thailand populations." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5343733" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5343733/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="642">Fig. 2D</figureCitation>
represents the original blue population from the 
<typeStatus id="045B52B6F25FFFC4FAB0F8912BD0F1C6" box="[1405,1451,1918,1942]" pageId="2" pageNumber="642">type</typeStatus>
locality on Semakau. On the inside of both right and left surstyli there are small bristles, that are black on the inside but pale on the border of the plate. A few small protuberances are also visible on the border of the plates.
</paragraph>
<caption id="8F9FBC9CF25EFFC5FF45F8F32FCDF18F" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5343733" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5343733" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5343733/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="643" startId="3.[136,171,1820,1842]" targetBox="[138,1474,294,1804]" targetPageId="3">
<paragraph id="DB5FEC14F25EFFC5FF45F8F32FCDF18F" blockId="3.[136,1475,1820,2015]" pageId="3" pageNumber="643">
Fig. 2. 
<taxonomicName id="1CE09797F25EFFC5FF1FF8F32FC6F161" authorityName="Grootaert &amp; Puniamoorthy" authorityYear="2014" box="[210,445,1820,1841]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Ngirhaphium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="643" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caeruleum">
<emphasis id="E9943006F25EFFC5FF1FF8F32FC6F161" box="[210,445,1820,1841]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="643">Ngirhaphium caeruleum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-complex. View of inside of the dorsal surstylus of the left side and the fused dorsal and ventral surstyli of the right side. Scale = 0.1mm. A, green 
<taxonomicName id="1CE09797F25EFFC5FDFEF8D62CE3F11E" authorityName="Grootaert &amp; Puniamoorthy" authorityYear="2014" box="[563,664,1849,1870]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Ngirhaphium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="643" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caeruleum">
<emphasis id="E9943006F25EFFC5FDFEF8D62CE3F11E" box="[563,664,1849,1870]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="643">caeruleum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Tutong, Brunei (ZRCBDP0066395) at 1.6 % from the Semakau population; B, green 
<taxonomicName id="1CE09797F25EFFC5FF2AF8B92F35F13B" authorityName="Grootaert &amp; Puniamoorthy" authorityYear="2014" box="[231,334,1878,1899]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Ngirhaphium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="643" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caeruleum">
<emphasis id="E9943006F25EFFC5FF2AF8B92F35F13B" box="[231,334,1878,1899]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="643">caeruleum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Pulau Tekong, Singapore (ZRCBDP0001462) at 0.6% from the Semakau population; C, green 
<taxonomicName id="1CE09797F25EFFC5FA96F8B92BB9F13B" authorityName="Grootaert &amp; Puniamoorthy" authorityYear="2014" box="[1371,1474,1878,1899]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Ngirhaphium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="643" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caeruleum">
<emphasis id="E9943006F25EFFC5FA96F8B92BB9F13B" box="[1371,1474,1878,1899]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="643">caeruleum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Pulau Ubin, Singapore (ZRC_BDP_0084430) at 0.6% from the Semakau population; D, blue 
<taxonomicName id="1CE09797F25EFFC5FB93F89D2AB8F1D7" authorityName="Grootaert &amp; Puniamoorthy" authorityYear="2014" box="[1118,1219,1906,1927]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Ngirhaphium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="643" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caeruleum">
<emphasis id="E9943006F25EFFC5FB93F89D2AB8F1D7" box="[1118,1219,1906,1927]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="643">caeruleum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the type locality on Semakau Island, Singapore (ZRCBDP0118762); E, green 
<taxonomicName id="1CE09797F25EFFC5FD04F8602D6DF1F4" authority="Samoh &amp; Satasook &amp; Grootaert, 2019" authorityName="Samoh &amp; Satasook &amp; Grootaert" authorityYear="2019" box="[713,790,1935,1956]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Ngirhaphium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="643" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="thaicum" status="new species">
<emphasis id="E9943006F25EFFC5FD04F8602D6DF1F4" box="[713,790,1935,1956]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="643">thaicum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel id="F2A78D7DF25EFFC5FCE8F87F2DE0F1F5" box="[805,923,1935,1957]" pageId="3" pageNumber="643" rank="species">new species</taxonomicNameLabel>
from Surat Thani, Thailand (24-018) at 4.2% from the Semakau population; F, green 
<taxonomicName id="1CE09797F25EFFC5FE73F8432C77F191" authority="Samoh &amp; Satasook &amp; Grootaert, 2019" authorityName="Samoh &amp; Satasook &amp; Grootaert" authorityYear="2019" box="[446,524,1964,1985]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Ngirhaphium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="643" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="thaicum" status="new species">
<emphasis id="E9943006F25EFFC5FE73F8432C77F191" box="[446,524,1964,1985]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="643">thaicum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel id="F2A78D7DF25EFFC5FDD6F8432CE8F192" box="[539,659,1964,1986]" pageId="3" pageNumber="643" rank="species">new species</taxonomicNameLabel>
from Cambodia (JP3C_Ngi-cambodiensis_Misc002) within the variability of the southern Thailand populations.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="DB5FEC14F259FFC2FFBCFF522FABF7C5" blockId="4.[112,753,189,405]" pageId="4" pageNumber="644">
The populations from 
<collectingCountry id="A3F7AC84F259FFC2FE96FF522FD8F685" box="[347,419,189,213]" name="Brunei" pageId="4" pageNumber="644">Brunei</collectingCountry>
(localities 
<collectingRegion id="192422F6F259FFC2FDDBFF512C1DF686" box="[534,614,190,214]" country="Brunei" name="Tutong" pageId="4" pageNumber="644">Tutong</collectingRegion>
, Berambang, and Labu, 
<figureCitation id="43DBF091F259FFC2FF10FF322F63F6A5" box="[221,280,221,245]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[113,148,979,1001]" captionTargetBox="[92,1469,170,978]" captionTargetId="figure-421@2.[92,1469,170,978]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 1. Haplotype network of the Ngirhaphium caeruleum-complex. Brunei: Berambang, Tutong, Labu; Singapore: Pulau Ubin, Pulau Tekong, Semakau Island; Thailand: Chumphon, Surat Thani, and Cambodia." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5343731" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5343731/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="644">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
) have the inside of the surstyli and the border covered with small black bristles without any tubercles. Both surstyli are comparatively wide and the tips are bluntly rounded (
<figureCitation id="43DBF091F259FFC2FF17FED22F48F705" box="[218,307,317,341]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[136,171,1820,1842]" captionTargetBox="[138,1474,294,1804]" captionTargetId="figure-8@3.[116,1482,277,1809]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 2. Ngirhaphium caeruleum-complex. View of inside of the dorsal surstylus of the left side and the fused dorsal and ventral surstyli of the right side. Scale = 0.1mm. A, green caeruleum from Tutong, Brunei (ZRCBDP0066395) at 1.6 % from the Semakau population; B, green caeruleum from Pulau Tekong, Singapore (ZRCBDP0001462) at 0.6% from the Semakau population; C, green caeruleum from Pulau Ubin, Singapore (ZRC_BDP_0084430) at 0.6% from the Semakau population; D, blue caeruleum from the type locality on Semakau Island, Singapore (ZRCBDP0118762); E, green thaicum, new species from Surat Thani, Thailand (24-018) at 4.2% from the Semakau population; F, green thaicum, new species from Cambodia (JP3C_Ngi-cambodiensis_Misc002) within the variability of the southern Thailand populations." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5343733" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5343733/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="644">Fig. 2A</figureCitation>
). The populations on Pulau Tekong and Pulau Ubin (
<figureCitation id="43DBF091F259FFC2FF30FEB22F08F725" box="[253,371,349,373]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[136,171,1820,1842]" captionTargetBox="[138,1474,294,1804]" captionTargetId="figure-8@3.[116,1482,277,1809]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 2. Ngirhaphium caeruleum-complex. View of inside of the dorsal surstylus of the left side and the fused dorsal and ventral surstyli of the right side. Scale = 0.1mm. A, green caeruleum from Tutong, Brunei (ZRCBDP0066395) at 1.6 % from the Semakau population; B, green caeruleum from Pulau Tekong, Singapore (ZRCBDP0001462) at 0.6% from the Semakau population; C, green caeruleum from Pulau Ubin, Singapore (ZRC_BDP_0084430) at 0.6% from the Semakau population; D, blue caeruleum from the type locality on Semakau Island, Singapore (ZRCBDP0118762); E, green thaicum, new species from Surat Thani, Thailand (24-018) at 4.2% from the Semakau population; F, green thaicum, new species from Cambodia (JP3C_Ngi-cambodiensis_Misc002) within the variability of the southern Thailand populations." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5343733" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5343733/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="644">Fig. 2B, C</figureCitation>
) have similar shaped surstyli as in 
<collectingCountry id="A3F7AC84F259FFC2FFBCFE922EC1F7C5" box="[113,186,381,405]" name="Brunei" pageId="4" pageNumber="644">Brunei</collectingCountry>
with short black bristles.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DB5FEC14F259FFC2FFBCFE512F2DF405" blockId="4.[113,753,445,597]" pageId="4" pageNumber="644">
In the Thai and Cambodian population both surstyli are distinctly more pointed (
<figureCitation id="43DBF091F259FFC2FE48FE322F81F7A5" box="[389,506,477,501]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[136,171,1820,1842]" captionTargetBox="[138,1474,294,1804]" captionTargetId="figure-8@3.[116,1482,277,1809]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 2. Ngirhaphium caeruleum-complex. View of inside of the dorsal surstylus of the left side and the fused dorsal and ventral surstyli of the right side. Scale = 0.1mm. A, green caeruleum from Tutong, Brunei (ZRCBDP0066395) at 1.6 % from the Semakau population; B, green caeruleum from Pulau Tekong, Singapore (ZRCBDP0001462) at 0.6% from the Semakau population; C, green caeruleum from Pulau Ubin, Singapore (ZRC_BDP_0084430) at 0.6% from the Semakau population; D, blue caeruleum from the type locality on Semakau Island, Singapore (ZRCBDP0118762); E, green thaicum, new species from Surat Thani, Thailand (24-018) at 4.2% from the Semakau population; F, green thaicum, new species from Cambodia (JP3C_Ngi-cambodiensis_Misc002) within the variability of the southern Thailand populations." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5343733" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5343733/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="644">Fig. 2E, F</figureCitation>
) and the tubercles on the border and sometimes on the inside of the surstyli are more pronounced. The inside of the plates are covered with short yellow bristles.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DB5FEC14F259FFC2FFBCFD922CBAF245" blockId="4.[112,754,637,1045]" pageId="4" pageNumber="644">
This distinct morphology and since the genetic distance of the Thai/Cambodian population is 4.2% apart from the 
<collectingCountry id="A3F7AC84F259FFC2FFBCFD522EA6F485" box="[113,221,701,725]" name="Singapore" pageId="4" pageNumber="644">Singapore</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry id="A3F7AC84F259FFC2FEDAFD522F1BF485" box="[279,352,701,725]" name="Brunei" pageId="4" pageNumber="644">Brunei</collectingCountry>
population let us decide to consider the Thai and Cambodian population as a different species. Considering it just as a variable species would only lead to loss of information linked to its ecology. The new species is described here below. If we consider the bio-species concept it might well be that the blue 
<taxonomicName id="1CE09797F259FFC2FE77FCB12C37F525" authorityName="Grootaert &amp; Puniamoorthy" authorityYear="2014" box="[442,588,861,885]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Ngirhaphium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="644" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caeruleum">
<emphasis id="E9943006F259FFC2FE77FCB12C37F525" box="[442,588,861,885]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="644">N. caeruleum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Semakau represents a distinct bio-species from the green specimens from the surrounding islands of 
<collectingCountry id="A3F7AC84F259FFC2FE75FC722C59F5E5" box="[440,546,925,949]" name="Singapore" pageId="4" pageNumber="644">Singapore</collectingCountry>
and the populations on 
<collectingCountry id="A3F7AC84F259FFC2FF58FC522E98F585" box="[149,227,957,981]" name="Brunei" pageId="4" pageNumber="644">Brunei</collectingCountry>
. However, the short genetic distance of 1–2% difference and the similar morphology except for the general body colour would render this species unrecognisable.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DB5FEC14F259FFC2FFBCFBD22CC6F205" blockId="4.[113,701,1085,1109]" box="[113,701,1085,1109]" pageId="4" pageNumber="644">
<emphasis id="E9943006F259FFC2FFBCFBD22F2DF205" bold="true" box="[113,342,1085,1109]" pageId="4" pageNumber="644">Haplotype network.</emphasis>
Number of sequences used: 114
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DB5FEC14F259FFC2FFBCFB922EA4F2E5" blockId="4.[113,752,1149,1205]" pageId="4" pageNumber="644">Total number of sites (excluding sites with gaps / missing data): 311</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DB5FEC14F259FFC2FFBCFB322FC9F2A5" blockId="4.[113,434,1245,1269]" box="[113,434,1245,1269]" pageId="4" pageNumber="644">Number of haplotypes, h: 31.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DB5FEC14F259FFC2FFBCFAF22F6FF165" blockId="4.[112,755,1309,1846]" pageId="4" pageNumber="644">
There are seven haplotypes of the 
<taxonomicName id="1CE09797F259FFC2FE35FAF22C11F365" authorityName="Grootaert &amp; Puniamoorthy" authorityYear="2014" box="[504,618,1309,1333]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Ngirhaphium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="644" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caeruleum">
<emphasis id="E9943006F259FFC2FE35FAF22C11F365" box="[504,618,1309,1333]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="644">caeruleum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
complex in 
<collectingCountry id="A3F7AC84F259FFC2FFBCFAD22EABF305" box="[113,208,1341,1365]" name="Thailand" pageId="4" pageNumber="644">Thailand</collectingCountry>
and one in 
<collectingCountry id="A3F7AC84F259FFC2FE8AFAD22FC3F305" box="[327,440,1341,1365]" name="Cambodia" pageId="4" pageNumber="644">Cambodia</collectingCountry>
. They are all unique as can be seen on 
<figureCitation id="43DBF091F259FFC2FF07FAB22F71F325" box="[202,266,1373,1397]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[113,148,979,1001]" captionTargetBox="[92,1469,170,978]" captionTargetId="figure-421@2.[92,1469,170,978]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 1. Haplotype network of the Ngirhaphium caeruleum-complex. Brunei: Berambang, Tutong, Labu; Singapore: Pulau Ubin, Pulau Tekong, Semakau Island; Thailand: Chumphon, Surat Thani, and Cambodia." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5343731" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5343731/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="644">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
. There is no connection shown on the figure between the Thai and the Singaporean population because the genetic distance (4.2%) is too far. The original blue 
<taxonomicName id="1CE09797F259FFC2FD4DFA722C95F3E5" authorityName="Grootaert &amp; Puniamoorthy" authorityYear="2014" box="[640,750,1437,1461]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Ngirhaphium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="644" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caeruleum">
<emphasis id="E9943006F259FFC2FD4DFA722C95F3E5" box="[640,750,1437,1461]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="644">caeruleum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
population is found on the island of Semakau. On Semakau Island there are only 2 haplotypes: 1 huge population and a very small one. The Semakau population is connected to the Pulau Ubin population where 5 haplotypes occur. One haplotype is shared with Semakau. Pulau Tekong, which is very close to Pulau Ubin has an own unique haplotype. This population seems to be connected to the populations on 
<collectingCountry id="A3F7AC84F259FFC2FFBCF9722EC6F0E5" box="[113,189,1693,1717]" name="Brunei" pageId="4" pageNumber="644">Brunei</collectingCountry>
. Remarkable is that the connection is by haplotypes occurring in the bay of 
<collectingCountry id="A3F7AC84F259FFC2FEBBF9522FC4F085" box="[374,447,1725,1749]" name="Brunei" pageId="4" pageNumber="644">Brunei</collectingCountry>
(Berambang and Labu) and not the population in 
<collectingRegion id="192422F6F259FFC2FEA7F9312FC3F0A6" box="[362,440,1758,1782]" country="Brunei" name="Tutong" pageId="4" pageNumber="644">Tutong</collectingRegion>
that is closer to 
<collectingCountry id="A3F7AC84F259FFC2FDB0F9322C94F0A5" box="[637,751,1757,1781]" name="Singapore" pageId="4" pageNumber="644">Singapore</collectingCountry>
. That population is well separated from the 2 sites in the Bay of 
<collectingCountry id="A3F7AC84F259FFC2FF09F8F22F6BF165" box="[196,272,1821,1845]" name="Brunei" pageId="4" pageNumber="644">Brunei</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
